In the 18th Century and prior some Christian denominations and groups--not all, but some--would declare anthros to be soulless beasts or demons. But I can see some groups like Quakers and maybe the Catholics saying, no, dude, they can speak and reason, we can talk to them and bring them the good news about Christ and God's plan for this world. They are people. God created them and they have souls that God values as much as He values ours. In the 21st Century, that would be the norm.

In other religions, Buddhism talks about reincarnation and transmigration of souls through different species, so from a theological perspective there would be no problem. Hinduism has that plus a monkey god, so they've already got a canon anthro.

Islam, well. I can see a variety of reactions, and in some places they would be declared demons and mullahs would be issuing fatwas of jihad, especially in places like Pakistan and Afghanistan and Somalia and Libya, maybe Egypt too. In Saudi Arabia and Morocco and Algeria they'd clamp down on that shit because it would be bad for business, and there might be an ugly incident or two requiring the government to put boot to ass, do some mass arrests, shut down some mosques and chop off some heads. In the UAE or Kuwait there probably wouldn't be, because it'd be bad for business. The streets of London and Paris and Stockholm and Munich would be extremely dangerous for anthros, though--parts would be as bad as Islamabad or Kabul. Not as dangerous as sub-Saharan Africa, though, where there would be people wanting to harvest their bones and organs for magic, like they already do to each other, especially when a child is born an albino.

In Taiwan, which retains a lot of the pre-Revolution, pre-industrialization cultural tendencies, anthros would be viewed as gods or maybe demons, depending on their appearance and behavior. In Japan they'd be an enormous instant novelty and in a week they'd be trying to talk them into being in porno movies.
